  "prompt": "What are some good romantic movies with unusual ideas?",
  "response": "Here are some romantic movies with unusual or unconventional ideas that stand out in their storytelling:\n\n1. **Eternal Sunshine of the Spotless Mind (2004)** - A mind-bending film about a couple who undergo a procedure to erase memories of each other. It explores the complexity of love, memory, and pain in relationships.\n\n2. **Her (2013)** - Set in a near-future world, this film follows a lonely man who falls in love with an artificial intelligence operating system, raising questions about love, intimacy, and technology.\n\n3. **The Lobster (2015)** - In a dystopian society where single people must find a partner within 45 days or be transformed into animals, this darkly comedic film explores themes of love and societal pressures.\n\n4. **Being John Malkovich (1999)** - A puppeteer finds a portal into the mind of actor John Malkovich. The film blends surrealism and romance, challenging notions of identity and desire.\n\n5. **Anomalisa (2015)** - A unique stop-motion animated film about a self-help author who perceives everyone in his life as having the same face and voice until he encounters a unique woman who changes his perspective.\n\n6. **The Science of Sleep (2006)** - A whimsical film about a man whose dreams interfere with his waking life, affecting his relationship with his neighbor. It intertwines reality and fantasy in endearing ways.\n\n7. **500 Days of Summer (2009)** - This non-linear romantic comedy-drama tells the story of a relationship from beginning to end, emphasizing that not all love stories have a traditional happy ending.\n\n8. **About Time (2013)** - A romantic comedy with a time travel twist, where the protagonist can relive moments in his life, prompting him to use this power to improve his romantic relationships and discover the importance of living in the moment.\n\n9. **The Shape of Water (2017)** - A fantastical love story between a mute woman and a mysterious sea creature, exploring themes of love and acceptance beyond societal norms.\n\n10. **Sylvia (2003)** - A biopic about the tumultuous relationship between poet Sylvia Plath and poet Ted Hughes, offering a glimpse into artistic love and the struggles of mental health.\n\nThese films bring fresh perspectives on romance and often challenge traditional tropes, making them memorable additions to the genre.",
